'''Princess Nakashi''' (? – after 455) was [[Empress of Japan]] as the consort of [[Emperor Ankō]].<ref>黛弘道 (1968-12). “継体天皇の系譜について : 釈日本紀所引上宮記逸文の研究”. 学習院史学 (学習院大学史学会) 5: 1-14. ISSN 0286-1658. NAID 110007562716.</ref> Nakashi was reviously married to Prince Ōkusaka, son of [[Emperor Nintoku]]. According to the [[Nihon Shoki|Nihongi]], Emperor Ankō had Okusaka executed (believing false accusations of disobedience), and, possibly in regret for unjustly executing Okusaka, took Nakashi as his own.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=roEfAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA331&dq=Nakashi+anko&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&source=gb_mobile_search&ovdme=1&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiviLqh7syHAxVVLTQIHelxN8gQ6AF6BAgMEAM#v=onepage&q=Nakashi%20anko&f=false |title=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697 |date=1896 |publisher=Society |isbn=978-0-524-05347-8 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Williams |first=Yoko |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=QVtUAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA88&dq=Nakashi+anko&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&source=gb_mobile_search&ovdme=1&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiviLqh7syHAxVVLTQIHelxN8gQ6AF6BAgNEAM#v=onepage&q=Nakashi%20anko&f=false |title=Tsumi - Offence and Retribution in Early Japan |date=2013-10-11 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-136-87422-2 |language=en}}</ref> She became a concubine of Emperor Ankō in 454 and was appointed empress 455. Emperor Anko came to love her greatly.<ref name=":0" />
Nakashi already had a child with her first husband, Okusaka. This child, Prince Mayuwa, was thereaftee raised in the imperial palace.<ref name=":0" />
She was the daughter of [[Emperor Richū]] and [[Princess Kusakanohatabino]].
